Reasoning: The claim that participating in six months of physical activity impairs cognitive functioning is refuted by the available evidence. A randomized controlled trial (Paper ID: 1642727) specifically investigated the effect of a 6-month physical activity program on cognitive function in older adults at risk for Alzheimer's disease. The study concluded that a "6-month program of physical activity provided a modest improvement in cognition over an 18-month follow-up period" (Proposition ID: prop_823, Chunk ID: chunk_17280). The abstract of this paper further states that participants in the intervention group (physical activity) showed improvement on the ADAS-Cog scale, while the usual care group deteriorated. No evidence was found to suggest that physical activity impairs cognitive functioning; instead, the direct evidence indicates an improvement.
